                  snippet:
                    "Emphasizing outcomes over process, this approach to remote employee management is perceived as empowering and expected to drive impressive gains in both productivity as well as workplace satisfaction and employee retention.\nInstead of focusing on how remote employees spend their time, leaders can benefit from prioritizing results while allowing employees to meet deliverables in a way that fully utilizes their unique skills and knowledge. Emphasizing outcomes over process, this approach to remote employee management is perceived as empowering and expected to drive impressive gains in both productivity as well as workplace satisfaction and employee retention.\nStill, several surveys suggest that remote employees see significant boosts in productivity, spurred in part by limited office distractions. These arrangements can also lead to major improvements in employee satisfaction, fueled by not only perceptions of greater work-life balance but also increased autonomy and an overall stronger sense of trust. While organization-specific benefits often dominate discussions surrounding remote work advantages, the wider-scale impact of these arrangements also warrants discussion.\nMoving forward, we may expect some organizations to shift away from remote work but others to express a renewed commitment\u2014no longer driven by public health mandates but rather documented benefits surrounding productivity, innovation, and workplace satisfaction.\nThe COVID-driven rise in remote work yielded several surprising findings, including a particularly striking takeaway: In spite of suffering major pandemic-related stressors, many people experienced considerable improvements in workplace satisfaction. Remote arrangements granted employees greater control over their day-to-day pursuits, allowing them to take much-needed breaks or tackle difficult tasks at times when they possessed the most energy or creativity.",
